Editor Comments to Author:\
\
First of all, I apologize for the length of time this was in review. In the end we were able to obtain two very thorough reviews, which were uniformly enthusiastic of the manuscript. We all agree that the authors are addressing a very difficult and timely problem in temporal genomics, and that this method is an important advancement in that area. \
\
Both reviewers raise important points that must be addressed prior to publication. First, both reviewers raise concerns about how dominance is treated in the model. Addressing these concerns will require additional simulations prior to publication.\
In addition, both reviewers have questions about the motivation/assumptions behind specification of the model, the sensitivity of the model to specific parameters, and the potential for unexplored areas of the parameter space to confound the model.\
\
Given that many methods are applied to situations that are outside their intended use (and give misleading results), I urge the authors to more clearly delineate scenarios/datasets that are within the situations it has been validated under. As best I can tell, the method assumes an island model or an island-continent model: this is the same assumption that FST outlier tests started with, and that island model assumption led to a lot of false positive results for those tests in more complex demographies. \'a0Thus, I also urge the authors to delineate scenarios that the method may encounter but would be outside the situations it has been validated under or its intended use. \'a0\
\
These suggestions can be addressed in the present manuscript without an increase in length by reducing the parts of the Discussion that are repetitive of the Results.\
\
