Comments to the Author\
The authors present a method for estimating the timing and strength of selection using temporally-spaced allele frequency data. I think this is a really interesting problem - allele frequencies can change due to the combined effects of drift, selection, and/or migration, and it can be sometimes be difficult to distinguish between these forces. Similar models implemented in the past have ignored drift by assuming an infinite population size and have struggled to incoporate migration. The model described here can incorporate both finite population size and island-continent migration and thus represents a significantly more realistic method for estimating selection. I think the writing style is quite clear overall, and though it was a bit technical for me at points (which is probably a function of my limited knowledge of the math involved) I really enjoyed reading the paper and I think the method looks very promising.\
\
I mainly have some minor requests for clarification regarding several parameters and assumptions of the model. It looks like four parameters (selection coefficient, selection time, migration rate, and migration time) are jointly estimated by the model, and there are a number of other parameters that must be fixed based on prior knowledge or estimated beforehand. I think there also may be some assumptions regarding how parameters can change over time or differ between the island and continent populations that are not made crystal clear. If the authors could clarify some of these assumptions, and perhaps test how violation of some of these assumptions might affect the inferences from the model, it would be very helpful to readers interested in using the model, and it would help to better characterize robustness of the model to violations of its assumptions. I'll go through each parameter separately:\
\
1) Selection coefficient (s): I am pretty sure that selection occurs only on the island, but this is not made completely clear. If selection occurred on the continent too (with either the same or a different coefficient) could this be incorporated into the model? And how would it affect inferences?\
\
2) Timing of selection (ts): Is selection coefficient assumed to be zero before selection begins, with an instantaneous transition to s at ts? I think it might be interesting to consider the robustness of the model other situations, e.g. where the allele under selection is slightly deleterious before selection, or when the selection coefficient gradually increases over time. Also in conjunction with 1) above it would be interesting to consider scenarios where there is selection in both populations but the timing and magnitude of selection differ among the two.\
\
3) Dominance coefficient (h): this I think must be fixed based on prior knowledge. it would be interesting to know how mis-specification of dominance could affect inference.\
\
4) Mutation is only briefly touched upon in the paper - the authors indicate that the model assumes the mutant allele under selection only arose once, and I think I am also making the assumption that this mutation arose before the onsert of selection (and potentially before the onset of simulations?). It's an interesting thought experiment to consider what would happen if mutations occurred during the simulations. If a beneficial mutation arose in the island population at a certain time tmut instead of the selection coefficient for an existing mutation changing at ts, I would think that the model might estimate tmut as ts. But perhaps those two situations could be distinguished because a completely novel mutation would begin at a lower frequency. Also interesting to think of what might happen if the mutation arose in the continent population - in that case the time of onset of migration could be conflated with ts. \
\
5) Is a monogenic trait assumed?\
\
I don't know whether the authors need to address all of these factors in the model or simulations but I think they should at least be addressed in the discussion.\
